<section id="one-trial-to-rule-them-all" class="reveal">
  <h2>One Pharma-Funded Trial Got FDA Approval</h2>
  <p>In December 2003, the FDA approved Zorbtive (somatropin) as the first medication ever licensed for short bowel syndrome. The entire approval rested on a single Phase III trial: 41 adults dependent on parenteral nutrition, randomized, placebo-controlled, double-blind. Patients receiving growth hormone plus glutamine plus a modified diet showed significantly greater reductions in IV feeding volume, calories, and infusion frequency. The sponsor was Serono, Inc., Zorbtive's manufacturer.</p>
  <p>Forty-one patients. One trial. One sponsor.</p>
  <p>Rare diseases get approved on thin evidence because large trials in small populations are genuinely hard to run. Fair enough. But the pivotal trial measured reductions in IV feeding volume over four weeks. It did not measure whether the gut was structurally healing. It was not designed to. And the difference between "patients needed less IV nutrition for a month" and "the intestine adapted" is the crack through which two decades of confusion poured.</p>
</section>

<section id="mechanism-without-durability" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Mechanism Works, the Drug Might Not</h2>
  <p>Growth hormone's proposed action in SBS is not crackpot physiology. GH stimulates insulin-like growth factor 1, which drives enterocyte proliferation and mucosal hyperplasia in the remaining intestine. More surface. More absorption. That is the pitch.</p>
  <p>Anders Dahlstrom, a Karolinska-trained pediatrician working at Stanford, tested it. His model was elegant: spontaneous dwarf rats born without the ability to produce growth hormone. Resect 60% of their small intestine and watch. Does the gut adapt without GH?</p>
  <p>It does. Mucosal hyperplasia proceeded normally. The structural growth that GH proponents credit to the drug happened fine without it. What failed was subtler. Accumulation of mucosal protein, including digestive hydrolases, was impaired. GH turned out to be required for functional maturation of the intestinal remnant. Not for growing more of it. Two <em>Pediatric Research</em> papers (1996 and 2001), funded by Swedish academic grants, no industry ties. The clinical debate spent the next two decades arguing about the wrong mechanism.</p>
  <p>Human trials fit the pattern. Scolapio's 1997 crossover: no significant difference in macronutrient absorption. Szkudlarek and Jeppesen's 2000 Danish study: energy, carbohydrate, fat, and nitrogen absorption identical between GH and placebo. Body weight rose during treatment. It vanished within two weeks. Lean body mass went up, but so did peripheral edema. Water, not muscle.</p>
  <p>The 2024 meta-analysis in the <em>Journal of Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition</em>, NIH-funded and replicated by a 2025 European cohort, found no significant difference in adaptation metrics between GH and placebo. Measure what the drug's proponents say it does, and the effect disappears. Measure a softer endpoint over a shorter window, and it shows up. That is not the profile of a drug that works. It is the profile of a drug that passed.</p>
</section>

<section id="conflicts-run-in-every-direction" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Conflicts Run in Every Direction</h2>
  <p>If the evidence against GH is this straightforward, why does the debate still feel unresolved? Because the people delivering the verdict have financial ties to the replacement.</p>
  <p>Vasquez consults for teduglutide producers. Prof. Mark Linden, whose 2023 review in <em>Gastroenterology</em> called GH benefits "short-lived and overstated," sells books on alternative nutrition therapies. Dr. Sarah Kline, whose 2025 paper in <em>Clinical Nutrition</em> found GH inferior to GLP-2 analogs, runs a monetized gut health coaching practice. Their meta-analyses are independently funded, partially replicated, and broadly consistent with each other. But the consulting relationships hand GH's remaining defenders exactly the ammunition they need to keep the conversation going.</p>
  <p>Professional societies compound the problem. ESPEN's 2023 guideline recommends teduglutide as first-choice and demotes GH to a secondary option. ESPEN receives corporate partnerships and congress sponsorship from Takeda, teduglutide's manufacturer. ASPEN receives corporate funding from Takeda, Nestlé Health Science, and Baxter. At its 2020 conference, the agenda listed a "Takeda Corporate Sponsored Breakfast" titled: "Reducing the need for Parenteral Support in patients with Short Bowel Syndrome through GATTEX."</p>
  <p>Disclosure is routinely mistaken for resolution. It is not. But a consulting relationship can bias which questions a researcher asks. It cannot fabricate absorption data that does not exist. The conflicts make the consensus slow to trust. They do not make it wrong.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Disclosure is routinely mistaken for resolution."</p></aside>

<section id="the-right-answer-costs-four-hundred-thousand" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Right Answer Costs $400,000 a Year</h2>
  <p>Teduglutide works. Phase III trials showed significant, sustained reductions in parenteral support. Some patients achieved enteral autonomy: freedom from IV feeding altogether. The clinical data is meaningfully stronger than anything that exists for growth hormone. The pivotal STEPS trial was funded by NPS Pharmaceuticals and Nycomed, a Takeda company. Loris Pironi, lead author of the ESPEN guideline, discloses advisory and grant/research support relationships with Takeda. Industry fingerprints everywhere. Results also everywhere.</p>
  <p>It costs between $300,000 and $400,000 per patient per year. A cost-effectiveness analysis in the <em>American Journal of Clinical Nutrition</em> found teduglutide cost $949,910 per quality-adjusted life year gained. Ten times the standard US threshold. The drug would need a price cut of more than 65% to meet conventional benchmarks.</p>
  <p>Zorbtive, whatever its limitations, is a four-week course. A market outcome wearing a lab coat displaced it.</p>
</section>

<section id="patient-caught-in-the-gap" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Patient Is Caught in the Gap</h2>
  <p>A person with short bowel syndrome is tethered to an IV pole several nights a week. Central venous catheter. Parenteral nutrition. Bloodstream infection. Thrombosis. Liver disease. Every night off the pump is a gain in safety and in something harder to quantify: a life that does not revolve around a tube.</p>
  <p>Two pharmacological options. One probably does not work, at least not the way its approval implied. The other works, costs more per year than most Americans earn, and was ushered into its guideline position by societies funded by its manufacturer. The one researcher whose basic science clarified what GH actually does in the gut, Dahlstrom, is a name most SBS clinicians have never heard, because animal studies funded by Swedish academic grants do not get promoted at Takeda-sponsored breakfast symposia.</p>
  <p>No one in this story lied. That is the unsettling part. Every actor followed the rules as designed. The system arrived at the right clinical answer and priced it out of reach, leaving the wrong answer on the shelf as the affordable alternative, defended by no one with clean hands.</p>
</section>

<section id="demand-better-architecture" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Fix Is Structural, Not Moral</h2>
  <p>Publicly funded replication trials. Guideline committees that exclude members with commercial ties to the drugs being ranked. Outcome measures chosen by people who do not benefit from the answer. Pricing structures that do not lock effective treatments behind a wall most healthcare systems cannot scale. Short bowel syndrome affects roughly 10,000 to 20,000 adults in the US. Rare enough that pharmaceutical companies hold outsized influence. Few enough that nobody else pays attention.</p>
  <p>The patient tethered to the IV pole deserves two things: an honest answer about what works, and the ability to access it. The evidence points to teduglutide. The price points away. Nobody in this debate is talking to you for free, and the drug that might actually help costs more than your house.</p>
</section>

